<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-774-472  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 774 472.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC World  Sept 1990 v8 n9 p225(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Words into print; tips for getting the most out of your wordprocessor. (includes a related article providing a macro forconverting ASCII files for use with Word 5.0, and a relatedarticle on keyboard file macros for WordPerfect 5.1) (tutorial)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Campbell, George.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Preparing a document for transfer from a word processor to adesktop publishing application can be facilitated by the followingsteps.andP;  Fonts should not be changed, nor should lines or boxes beincluded.andP;  Multiple columns and centered, hyphenated and justifiedtext should be avoided.andP;  Text should be single-spaced andparagraphs separated by a single carriage return.andP;  Only one spaceshould be used after a period, and initial paragraph lines shouldnot be indented.andP;  Attached style sheets must be disabled.andP;  Tablesand charts should be created using either single tabs or carriagereturns as field separators.andP;  Use separate files for graphics,tables, footnotes, and sidebars.andP;  Embed bracketed comments indocuments to indicate graphics locations and special formatting.andO;For word processors that have no conversion, save files in ASCIIformat.andP;  Communicate with the desktop publisher, providingsketches or printouts and noting font choices or other formatting.andO;Consider embedding the desktop publishing package's formattingcodes in the word processing document if the desktop package isregularly used.andP;  A conversion macro for WordPerfect 5.0 and 5.1 isprovided that removes gaps between paragraphs, extra spacesbetween sentences, and changes double tabs to single tabs.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     TutorialWord ProcessingDesktop PublishingFilesMacros.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>